mistral.reason: Hairspray (2007 film) does address the issue of racial segregation during the Civil Rights Movement era, but it is not about the African-American Civil Rights Movement (1954–68). Instead, it is set in Baltimore during the 1960s and focuses on a white teenager, Tracy Turnblad, who advocates for integration and equality among races. The film sheds light on racial tensions of the time but does not directly follow or depict the major events and milestones of the African-American Civil Rights Movement as they unfolded from 1954 to 1968.

gemma2.reason: Several passages mention the film addressing racial integration and segregation but none explicitly state it focuses on the entirety of the Civil Rights Movement.

llama3.1.reason: The film Hairspray (2007) primarily focuses on themes of racial integration, body positivity, and the empowerment of a white teenage girl, Tracy Turnblad, rather than specifically highlighting or depicting the African-American Civil Rights Movement.
